Based on some of my recent investigations into other crossgen outerloop failures, I believe what's happening in these two tests is that composite R2R is not inlining methods that we expect to be inlined. This happened for example in https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/issues/117823 where in composite mode on certain targets, no inlining was happening for the target rejitted method, and the test was written with an expectation that the method would have been inlined.

In particular, the forceinlining PositiveCases failure indicates that inlining did not match expectations inside of a finally block, *either* due to a method being inlined that we didn't expect to be inlined (this could change at any time and is definitely not a regression), or because a method we aggressiveinlining'd wasn't inlined. 

`FAIL -- Unexpected inlining result in: Finally block`

For readability here's decompiled C# for the relevant IL:
```csharp
	finally
	{
		if (!A1(a, b, c) || A2(a, b, c))
		{
			V_0 = "Finally block";
		}
	}
	if (V_0 != null)
	{
		Console.WriteLine("FAIL -- Unexpected inlining result in: " + V_0);
		return 0;
	}
```
And the return values of A1 & A2 indicate whether they were inlined or not (true if inlined). So this test expects A1 to be inlined, and A2 to not be inlined, due to A1 having an AggressiveInlining flag and A2 not having it.

This is likely a behavior change like the other ones I've seen - we used to inline the method and now we don't - but I can't think of any circumstances where composite R2R choosing not to inline an AggressiveInlining method would cause serious breakage other than applications that are nearly out of stack. At worst it should only regress performance due to call overhead, unless you're already so close to overflowing stack that a couple extra call frames cause you to hit the limit. In that scenario basically anything could break you.

If the failure was caused by A2 getting inlined when it wasn't expected to, that is *definitely* not a regression - it's not guarded with NoInlining so it's completely legal to inline it. I'm not sure why the test goes out of its way to check this.

Overall it doesn't seem like AggressiveInlining is or was meant to be a guarantee, so it should be perfectly legal for the JIT or for R2R or for NativeAOT to choose not to inline an AggressiveInlining method. The documentation agrees with this:
> The method should be inlined if possible.
